@NODE overview "Overview"

Incredible as it may sound - I've discovered a useful feature of
WINDOWS '95 %-■ : The autostart function for CDs.
4 months ago I finally bought a CD-ROM drive. I soon started annoying at
pressing thousands of buttons before being able to run a special CD. So I
tried to port the autostart function to the AMIGA :-)

2 script files per disk ("Autostart" can also be used with any other type
of changeable disk - there is no limitation to CDs) can be created : one
will be started whenever you insert the disk, the other when you remove it.
Thus it is possible e.g. to automatically remove ASSIGNs created to use a
CD when it is removed (so you aren't asked all the time to re-insert it).

As "Autostart" is my first useful C program, I needed some time for the
development. Besides, every time I try to call the function "ArgArrayInit",
my computer crahes. So I had to avoid it, adding to the length of the
program.

P.S.
Because this is my first shareware program, you're just reading my first
documentation (world premiere ;-) ) ! In order not to forget important
points, I used the documentation of the C64 emulator "FRODO" as a model.
@ENDNODE

@NODE system "System requirements"

To use "Autostart", you need :

À   An Amiga with Kickstart 2.04 or higher

À   The shell command EXECUTE in your command path

À   Drives to auto-start :-)

À   ARexx is also recommended (@{"ARexx port" LINK arexx})
@ENDNODE

@NODE install "Installation"

Installation is rather easily done by the Installer. For all those who
prefer a manual installation (???), here are the instructions :

À   Copy "Autostart" to any directory you want (e.g. WBStartup).

À   Create two directories for the script files. Alternatively you can
    simply copy the directories "Insert_Scripts" and "Remove_Scripts" from
    the Autostart directory.

À   Change the program's preferences via the @{"tooltypes" LINK tooltypes}.

À   Insert disks ;-)
@ENDNODE

@NODE usage "Usage"

Everytime you insert or remove a directory in/from one of the specified
drives, "Autostart" will execute a certain script file. You need to specify
two directories - one for the insert scripts and one for the remove scripts
(see also @{"tooltypes" LINK tooltypes}).

There must be an own file for every disk which shall be used by Autostart,
carrying the same name as the disk (but @{b}without@{ub} colon - you couldn't
create one with colon, anyway ;-) ). There are already some ready-to-use
example scripts in your installation directory.

As many CDs (especially shareware collections) need certain assigns, it is
a good idea to insert them into the insert script. But it is impossible to
remove them by adding "ASSIGN...REMOVE" to the remove script, as you would
then have to reinsert the disk after removing it (and aside from the fact
that this would be rather stupid, the assigns would be re-created by
Autostart !). For this purpose I wrote the accessory @{"RemAssign" LINK remassign}, which is
included in this software package.
@ENDNODE

@NODE tnt "Tips & tricks"

CDs needing special assigns usually contain a script to create them - on
Meeting Pearls CDs (at least Nos. 3 and 4) you can find it in the directory
SYSTEM/S. Meeting Pearls IV even has a special de-install script !

These script files can easily be modificated to use them as Autostart
scripts.
@ENDNODE

@NODE shell "Shell parameters"

Here's the template for running "Autostart" from the shell :

@{b}AUTOSTART@{ub} CHECK/A,I=INSERT/K,R=REMOVE/K,O=ONSTARTUP/S,D=DISABLE/K,P=PRIORITY/N

@{b}À   CHECK@{ub}
    Specifies the drives to be checked by "Autostart"; several drives can
    be separated using the "|" character.
    E.g.: CHECK=CD0:|DF0: Checks for disks in the drives CD0 and DF0
    @{u}This parameter must be specified !@{uu}

@{b}À   INSERT@{ub}

    This parameter (shortcut "I") specifies the path to the scripts which
    shall be executed if you insert a disk. If INSERT is not given, the
    default "Insert_Scripts:" will be used.

@{b}À   REMOVE@{ub}
    Just like INSERT, but for removed disks. Default : "Remove_Scripts:".
    Shortcut : "R".

@{b}À   ONSTARTUP@{ub}
    If this parameter is given, all disks inserted when starting "Autostart"
    will be considered as if you'd just inserted them. Shortcut : "O".

@{b}À   DISABLE@{ub}
    As long as you press the key combination specified here, "Autostart"
    will ignore any disks you insert or remove. The default is "CONTROL F1";
    shortcut : "D".

@{b}À   ACTIVATE@{ub}
    Every time you press this key combination, the insert scripts for all inserted
    disks will be executed (just like running "Autostart" with the "ONSTARTUP"
    option given). Default : "CONTROL F2"

@{b}À   PRIORITY@{ub}
    Specifies the program's priority ("Autostart" is a commodity).
    Default : 0
@ENDNODE

@NODE tooltypes "ToolTypes"

You can configure "Autostart" using the following tooltypes :

@{b}À   CHECK@{ub}
    Here you can specify the drives which are to be checked by "Autostart".
    Several drives can be separated using the "|" character.
    E.g.: CHECK=CD0:|DF0: Checks for disks in the drices CD0 and DF0
    @{u}This tooltype must be specified !@{uu}

@{b}À   INSERT@{ub}
    Specifies the path to the scripts which shall be executed when you
    insert a disk. Default is "Insert_Scripts:"

@{b}À   REMOVE@{ub}
    Just as INSERT, but for removed disks. Default : "Remove_Scripts:"

@{b}À   ONSTARTUP@{ub}
    If this parameter is specified, all disks inserted when starting
    "Autostart" will be considered as if you'd just inserted them.

@{b}À   DISABLE@{ub}
    As long as you press the key combination specified here, "Autostart"
    will completely ignore any disks you insert or remove. Default :
    "CONTROL F1".

@{b}À   ACTIVATE@{ub}
    Allows you to specify a key combination which will cause "Autostart"
    to execute the insert scripts for all currently inserted disks, just
    as if you ran "Autostart" with the "ONSTARTUP" option given. Default :
    "CONTROL F2".

@{b}À   CX_PRIORITY @{ub}
    Specifies the program's priority ("Autostart" is a commodity).
    Default : 0
@ENDNODE

@NODE arexx "ARexx"

Offering an ARexx port, "Autostart" supports the following ARexx-commands :

@{b}À   ACTIVATE@{ub}
    Executes the insert-scripts for all inserted disks

@{b}À   ENABLE
À   DISABLE@{ub}
    Turns drive checking on/off. This can be undone by pressing the
    corresponding key combination.

@{b}À   QUIT@{ub}
    Exits Autostart
@ENDNODE

@NODE remassign "RemAssign"

RemAssign is a small program which can be used as a shell command to remove
all assignes referring to a certain volume - no matter whether the volume
is inserted or not!

@{u}Usage :@{uu}

@{b}RemAssign@{ub} Volume

@{b}Volume@{ub} : The @{b}volume@{ub}, from which you want to remove all assigns
         (without terminating colon!)

If you run RemAssign from a shell window, you will be informed how many
assigns have been removed.
@ENDNODE

